    "summary": "This section answers retrieval queries regarding daily active playtime patterns, session structures, and retention mechanics in 4X strategy games.\n**Topics & Definitions:** Explains the \"honeymoon period\" (initial engagement phase), the \"high-frequency, low-duration\" session model (mindshare model), and the \"social watershed\" (retention divergence point). Contrasts 4X engagement loops with MOBA/RPG genres.\n**Entities & Player Segments:** 4X strategy games, MOBA/RPG titles, core paying users (\"whales\"), alliance members, solo players.\n**Dates/Timeframes:** First week (honeymoon phase), Day 1 (initial engagement peak), Day 7 (social integration threshold).\n**Metrics:** \n- Honeymoon: 40–60 min/day average; whales 1.5–3 hrs/day; Day 1 peak ~90 min.\n- Session frequency & distribution: 8–12 sessions/day; 70% short checks (3–5 min) for resource maintenance; 30% deep engagement (20–45 min) for events/activities.\n- Day 7 divergence: Alliance players ≥45 min/day; solo players <20 min/day; build cooldowns extend to 4–8 hrs.\n**Claims:** 4X games depend on frequent, variable-length sessions rather than continuous play. Playtime sustainability after Day 7 is entirely contingent on social integration (alliance participation). Prolonged build cooldowns create a critical retention risk for solo players.\n**Evidence Types:** Quantitative behavioral metrics, comparative genre analysis, causal retention assertions.\n**Procedures/Tables/Figures:** None specified in this section."
